column45: Generally for textbooks, I will find a torrent or pdf version of it online. It may be the current edition, or a previous edition. These are generally lower quality, and are harder to read on a computer screen. However, the quality of the information is generally the same. I do end up spending money on textbooks, as some texts are not available online, or the can have an online component (such as Mastering Biology, etc.). For most courses, I use the textbook mostly for the glossary. I have had textbooks that do not  have a glossary, leading me to search through each passage of text for the definition of a term or using the internet to find a satisfactory definition. The open textbook used in this course has a very practical glossary section at the end of each chapter. The text passages are easy to read and have a lot of helpful examples.

column86: My experience has been very good. I do not have a lot of experience, mainly just using the BC open textbook for my course. Using this resource has saved me a lot of time and money, allowing me to help pay for insurance for my car.

column86: I have an open textbook for my second semester introduction to sociology course that I use often and I find quite handy. I appreciate not having to pay for a textbook as there are very unreasonably priced and it is handy to simply have it on the internet. I also have an open textbook in my biology class and this one is there but it is simply optional to use. I do not feel like I'm learning any less but sometimes there will be questions on exams that we did not cover in class. Which is what I find troubling because it can be hard to base exams off simply what we go over in class without having the secondary material of a textbook to go off on.
